        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer69445438" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11710376630080372181">So, I was really impressed by Hard Love but Love and Lies isn&apos;t quite as good. <br/><br/>Things I liked about it:<br/>1) I like Marisol as a character<br/>2) It&apos;s set in Cambridge and I recognized many of the places and the band Girlyman (that was exciting to see the name of one of my favorite bands in print!)<br/>3) I liked having Gio as a secondary character. It was interesting having Marisol as the main character and Gio as the secondary instead of the way around. And he understood her well. <br/>4) I liked the creative, </span>
  <span id="freeText11710376630080372181" style="display:none">So, I was really impressed by Hard Love but Love and Lies isn't quite as good. <br /><br />Things I liked about it:<br />1) I like Marisol as a character<br />2) It's set in Cambridge and I recognized many of the places and the band Girlyman (that was exciting to see the name of one of my favorite bands in print!)<br />3) I liked having Gio as a secondary character. It was interesting having Marisol as the main character and Gio as the secondary instead of the way around. And he understood her well. <br />4) I liked the creative, literary parts that are always in Wittlinger's novels<br /><br />What I didn't like:<br />1) The plot and eventual ending was sooooooo cliched and predictable. Not original, except maybe that Marisol is gay. And really, that's enough to cut a star. <br /><br />You can read Love and Lies without having read Hard Love first, there's a summary of Hard Love in the first couple chapters. But Hard Love might be ruined for you.</span>
