  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_352761086" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/352761086" />
    <a title="R" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/10364202-r"><img alt="R" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/352761086?book_show_action=true">Jun 21, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="R" class="user" itemprop="url" name="R" href="/user/show/10364202-r">R</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/10364202-r?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/10364202-r?shelf=lesbian">lesbian</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer352761086" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8000991454575294169">I read Hard Love several times over the course of a couple years before I discovered this spin off. Because Marisol Guzman was my favorite character in Hard Love, I was delighted and immediately ordered the book. I think Wittlinger has a good sense for her readers wants because I imagine a lot of the people reading Hard Love were reading it for the LGBT components. It only makes sense to write a follow up from the POV of the main lesbian character.<br/><br/>I&apos;ll admit this book is very predictable and sim</span>
  <span id="freeText8000991454575294169" style="display:none">I read Hard Love several times over the course of a couple years before I discovered this spin off. Because Marisol Guzman was my favorite character in Hard Love, I was delighted and immediately ordered the book. I think Wittlinger has a good sense for her readers wants because I imagine a lot of the people reading Hard Love were reading it for the LGBT components. It only makes sense to write a follow up from the POV of the main lesbian character.<br /><br />I'll admit this book is very predictable and simple. But I don't think that's always a bad thing. Sometimes you don't want drama and plot twists and surprises around every turn. This isn't that kind of book. It's a parallel to Hard Love that shows Gio and Marisol going through very similar emotions about love (and lies). It's nice to read these side by side and compare them. Maybe this book has a "cheesier" love story than Hard Love, but it's queer representation and as a queer reader that's important to me. Maybe the plot isn't original, but the characters are.<br /><br />Marisol does seem "tougher" in Hard Love, but in Love and Lies you get to see her soft side and her inner monologue. We knew the toughness was an act before hand and that she didn't have as hard an interior as an exterior, so it's nice to see a different side of her - even though I did appreciate her level-headed coolness in Hard Love.<br /><br />Overall, it's not the most interesting and original plot line, but the characters are good (even the static, supporting ones like Diana Tree and the waitress and pie maker at the coffee shop Marisol works at) and it's a nice young adult read that teens can relate to and learn some things from. As a writer, I also enjoyed the elements involving literature (Marisol writing her first novel, Marisol and Gio going to a writing class every Saturday). I'm really happy I picked this book up, and I've read it many times. If anything in this story sounds interesting to you, don't hesitate to read it. It's one of my favorites.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8000991454575294169" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


