<div id="review_44540733" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/44540733" />
    <a title="Teen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1387901-teen"><img alt="Teen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1217886436p2/1387901.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/44540733?book_show_action=true">Jan 27, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Teen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Teen" href="/user/show/1387901-teen">Teen</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1387901-teen?shelf=lgbtiq">lgbtiq</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer44540733" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6954041204092513700">Review: [sequel to Hard Love:] Marisol is taking the year after high school off, but she has given herself two assignments: she will write her first novel &amp; she will fall in love. Marisol finds two birds in the bush when she falls in love with her elegant, inspirational and seemingly competent writing teacher, Olivia. Talk about the Teacher’s Pet! Unfortunately Marisol’s real chance for love is a fellow gay teen, Lee from Indiana. Thank heavens, Gio, Marisol’s friend from “Hard Love” is there to</span>
  <span id="freeText6954041204092513700" style="display:none">Review: [sequel to Hard Love:] Marisol is taking the year after high school off, but she has given herself two assignments: she will write her first novel &amp; she will fall in love. Marisol finds two birds in the bush when she falls in love with her elegant, inspirational and seemingly competent writing teacher, Olivia. Talk about the Teacher’s Pet! Unfortunately Marisol’s real chance for love is a fellow gay teen, Lee from Indiana. Thank heavens, Gio, Marisol’s friend from “Hard Love” is there to help her steer through all the fake stuff in her path to her truth. If the inside flap did not state that Ellen Wittlinger lives with her husband in MA, I would swear this book is autobiographical; I suppose that’s a testament to Wittlinger’s writing. At the end of the end of the book, the reader will find “Quotations on Writing,” which Olivia has tried to pass off as her own, but Wittlinger let’s us know which author each quote is attributed to. I like E.L. Doctorow’s: “Writing a novel is like driving a car at night. You can only see as far as your headlights, but you can make the whole trip that way.” Peg Dombek</span>
  <a data-text-id="6954041204092513700" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


